  "A subset W must satisfy three conditions to be a subspace: (1) the zero vector is in W, (2) W is closed under addition, and (3) W is closed under scalar multiplication. All other vector space axioms are inherited from V.": "",
  "Which of the following is always a subspace of any vector space V?": "",
  "The set containing only the zero vector": "",
  "The empty set": "",
  "Any finite subset of V": "",
  "The set of all unit vectors": "",
  "The set {0} containing only the zero vector is always a subspace (called the trivial subspace or zero subspace). It contains the zero vector, and 0 + 0 = 0 and c * 0 = 0 for any scalar c, so closure holds.": "",
  "Is the set of all vectors (x, y, z) in R^3 where x + y + z = 0 a subspace of R^3?": "",
  "Yes, but only if we restrict to positive values": "",
  "Yes, it satisfies all three subspace conditions": "",
