  "The line y = 2x + 1 does not pass through the origin, so the zero vector (0, 0) is not in the set (since 0 ≠ 2(0)+1 = 1). A subspace must contain the zero vector, so this is not a subspace.": "",
  "If W1 and W2 are both subspaces of V, is their intersection W1 ∩ W2 also a subspace of V?": "",
  "No, never": "",
  "Yes, always": "",
  "Only if W1 = W2": "",
  "Only if V is finite-dimensional": "",
  "The intersection of any collection of subspaces is always a subspace. The zero vector is in both, so it is in the intersection. If u and v are in both W1 and W2, then u+v is in both (by closure in each), so u+v is in the intersection. Similarly for scalar multiplication.": "",
  "Is the union W1 ∪ W2 of two subspaces W1 and W2 necessarily a subspace?": "",
  "Yes, if V is finite-dimensional": "",
  "No, unless one is contained in the other": "",
  "The union of two subspaces is a subspace if and only if one is contained in the other. For example, in R^2, the x-axis and y-axis are both subspaces, but their union is not closed under addition: (1,0) + (0,1) = (1,1) is not on either axis.": "",
  "The set of all 2x2 matrices with zero trace (sum of diagonal entries equals zero) is a subset of the space of all 2x2 matrices. Is it a subspace?": "",
