  "No, it is not closed under addition": "",
  "Yes, it contains the zero vector and is closed under addition": "",
  "Yes, it is the union of two quadrants which are subspaces": "",
  "While (0,0) is in S and S is closed under scalar multiplication, it is not closed under addition. For example, (1, 1) and (-1, 2) are both in S (since 1*1=1>=0 and (-1)*2=-2, wait, (-1)(2) = -2 < 0, so (-1,2) is not in S). Take (2, -1) with 2*(-1) = -2 < 0, not in S. Actually, let's use (1, 0) and (0, -1) both in S, sum is (1, -1) with 1*(-1) = -1 < 0, not in S.": "",
  "Which of the following is a subspace of P_3 (polynomials of degree at most 3)?": "",
