  "That the subset is linearly independent": "",
  "The subspace test is a shortcut: instead of checking all 10 axioms, you only need to verify three conditions for a subset W of V: (1) the zero vector is in W, (2) W is closed under addition, and (3) W is closed under scalar multiplication. The remaining axioms are inherited from V.": "",
  "What does it mean for a subspace to be 'proper'?": "",
  "It has even dimension": "",
  "It satisfies additional axioms beyond the standard ones": "",
  "It contains only proper fractions as scalars": "",
  "It is a subspace that is neither the zero subspace nor the entire vector space": "",
  "A proper subspace is a subspace W of V such that W is not equal to {0} and W is not equal to V. In other words, it is a subspace that is strictly between the trivial subspace and the full space.": "",
  "What is the 'sum' of two subspaces W1 and W2?": "",
  "The set {w1 + w2 : w1 in W1, w2 in W2}": "",
  "The Cartesian product W1 x W2": "",
  "The intersection W1 ∩ W2": "",
  "The union W1 ∪ W2": "",
  "The sum of two subspaces W1 + W2 is the set of all vectors that can be written as w1 + w2 where w1 is in W1 and w2 is in W2. This sum is always a subspace and is the smallest subspace containing both W1 and W2.": "",
  "What does 'direct sum' of subspaces mean?": "",
  "A sum W1 + W2 where every vector in the sum can be written uniquely as w1 + w2, equivalently W1 ∩ W2 = {0}": "",
  "The sum of the dimensions of the subspaces": "",
  "The union of two subspaces": "",
  "A subspace formed by scalar multiples only": "",
  "The direct sum W1 ⊕ W2 is the sum W1 + W2 with the additional condition that W1 ∩ W2 = {0}. This guarantees that every vector in the sum has a unique decomposition as w1 + w2.": "",
  "What is meant by 'the subspace spanned by a set S'?": "",
  "The smallest subspace containing all elements of S, consisting of all linear combinations of vectors in S": "",
  "The set of vectors orthogonal to S according to conventional analysis": "",
  "The set S itself, particularly regarding that under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "The largest subspace contained in S following conventional understanding": "",
  "The subspace spanned by S (denoted span(S)) is the intersection of all subspaces containing S, which equals the set of all possible linear combinations of vectors in S. It is the smallest subspace that contains every vector in S.": "",
  "What is the relationship between a subspace and the original vector space's operations?": "",
  "A subspace inherits addition but defines its own scalar multiplication": "",
