  "What is a 'complementary subspace'?": "",
  "A subspace that contains all vectors not in W": "",
  "A subspace with the same dimension as W": "",
  "The set of vectors orthogonal to W": "",
  "A subspace W' such that V = W ⊕ W' (direct sum), meaning every vector in V has a unique decomposition": "",
  "A complementary subspace W' to a subspace W in V is a subspace such that V = W ⊕ W', meaning W + W' = V and W ∩ W' = {0}. Every vector in V can be uniquely written as w + w' with w in W and w' in W'.": "",
  "A civil engineer models the deflection of a bridge at 5 points along its length as a vector in R^5. The set of feasible deflection patterns must satisfy three constraints: the deflection at the two endpoints is zero (positions 1 and 5). She represents this as {(0, x2, x3, x4, 0) : x2, x3, x4 in R}. Is this set a subspace of R^5?": "",
  "No, because it has only 3 free variables": "",
  "Only if the deflections are positive": "",
  "No, because it does not include all of R^5": "",
  "Yes, because it contains the zero vector, and is closed under addition and scalar multiplication": "",
  "The zero vector (0,0,0,0,0) is in the set. Adding two vectors of the form (0,x2,x3,x4,0) gives (0,x2+y2,x3+y3,x4+y4,0) which is also in the set. Scaling gives (0,cx2,cx3,cx4,0). All three subspace conditions are met, so this is a subspace of R^5.": "",
  "A communications engineer studies the set of all signals f(t) on [0, T] that satisfy f(0) = f(T) (periodic boundary conditions). She claims this set is a subspace of the vector space of all continuous functions on [0, T]. Is she correct?": "",
  "No, because periodic functions cannot be added": "",
  "Yes, because the constraint f(0) = f(T) is preserved under addition and scalar multiplication": "",
  "No, because f(0) = f(T) is a nonlinear constraint": "",
