  "The zero function satisfies 0 = 0. If f(0) = f(T) and g(0) = g(T), then (f+g)(0) = f(0)+g(0) = f(T)+g(T) = (f+g)(T). Similarly, (cf)(0) = cf(0) = cf(T) = (cf)(T). All subspace conditions are satisfied.": "",
  "A financial analyst constructs portfolios as vectors in R^10 where each component is the weight of an asset. She restricts to portfolios where weights sum to 1. Does this set form a subspace of R^10?": "",
  "No, because R^10 is too high-dimensional": "",
