  "The zero vector (0,...,0) has weights summing to 0, not 1, so it is not in this set. Without the zero vector, the set cannot be a subspace. Additionally, adding two portfolios with weights summing to 1 gives weights summing to 2. This is an affine subspace, not a (linear) subspace.": "",
  "A computer scientist stores n-bit binary strings as vectors in {0, 1}^n. She considers the set of all codewords in a linear code (closed under XOR, which acts like addition mod 2). Over the field GF(2), is this set a subspace?": "",
  "Only if n is even": "",
  "No, because binary strings are not real-valued vectors": "",
