  "No, because XOR is not real addition": "",
  "A linear code is precisely a subspace of GF(2)^n, where GF(2) = {0, 1} is the field with two elements. Closure under XOR (addition mod 2) and containing the zero codeword are exactly the subspace conditions over this field.": "",
  "A mechanical engineer analyzes vibration modes of a structure. Each mode is a vector in R^100 representing displacements. She discovers that any linear combination of the first three modes is also a valid mode. What can she conclude about the set of these combinations?": "",
