  "An audio engineer models sound signals as vectors in a function space. She considers the set of all signals f(t) satisfying f(t) = -f(-t) (odd functions). Is this a subspace of the space of all continuous functions on [-1, 1]?": "",
  "No, because the product of two odd functions is even, not odd": "",
  "No, because odd functions are always nonzero at t = 0": "",
  "Only if we also include even functions": "",
  "Yes, because the sum of odd functions is odd, a scalar multiple of an odd function is odd, and the zero function is odd": "",
  "The zero function satisfies 0 = -0, so it is odd. If f(t) = -f(-t) and g(t) = -g(-t), then (f+g)(t) = f(t)+g(t) = -f(-t)-g(-t) = -(f+g)(-t). Similarly, (cf)(t) = cf(t) = c(-f(-t)) = -(cf)(-t). All subspace conditions hold.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical researcher represents drug formulations as vectors in R^8, where each component is the concentration of an ingredient. She requires all concentrations to be non-negative. Does this constraint define a subspace?": "",
